thrm{M_\\odot}$ range. The constraints on the EoS are shallow, but\nwe show how they will tighten as the knowledge on the jet incidence improves.\nWe also discuss how to extend the method to include future BNS mergers, with\npossibly uncertain jet associations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 3 Feb 2022 16:09:38 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 7 Jun 2022 22:11:48 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 29 Jul 2022 13:34:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-26"}
{"id":"2202.01657","submitter":"Annika Str\\\"omer","authors":"Annika Str\\\"omer, Christian Staerk, Nadja Klein, Leonie Weinhold,\n  Stephanie Titze, Andreas Mayr","title":"Deselection of Base-Learners for Statistical Boosting -- with an\n  Application to Distributional Regression","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"stat.ME stat.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a new procedure for enhanced variable selection for component-wise\ngradient boosting. Statistical boosting is a computational approach that\nemerged from machine learning, which allows to fit regression models in the\npresence of high-dimensional data. Furthermore, the algorithm can lead to\ndata-driven variable selection. In practice, however, the final models\ntypically tend to include too many variables in some situations. This occurs\nparticularly for low-dimensional data (p<n), where we observe a slow\noverfitting behavior of boosting. As a result, more variables get included into\nthe final model without altering the prediction accuracy. Many of these false\npositives are incorporated with a small coefficient and therefore have a small\nimpact, but lead to a larger model. We try to overcome this issue by giving the\nalgorithm the chance to deselect base-learners with minor importance. We\nanalyze the impact of the new approach on variable selection and prediction\nperformance in comparison to alternative methods including boosting with\nearlier stopping as well as twin boosting. We illustrate our approach with data\nof an ongoing cohort study for chronic kidney disease patients, where the most\ninfluential predictors for the health-related quality of life measure are\nselected in a distributional regression approach based on beta regression.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 3 Feb 2022 16:10:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-02-04"}
