{"id":"2202.01901","submitter":"June Wunder","authors":"june wunder, Arthur Azevedo de Amorim, Patrick Baillot, Marco Gaboardi","title":"Bunched Fuzz: Sensitivity for Vector Metrics","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.PL","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Program sensitivity measures the distance between the outputs of a program\nwhen run on two related inputs. This notion, which plays a key role in areas\nsuch as data privacy and optimization, has been the focus of several program\nanalysis techniques introduced in recent years. Among the most successful ones,\nwe can highlight type systems inspired by linear logic, as pioneered by Reed\nand Pierce in the Fuzz programming language. In Fuzz, each type is equipped\nwith its own distance, and sensitivity analysis boils down to type checking. In\nparticular, Fuzz features two product types, corresponding to two different\nnotions of distance: the tensor product combines the distances of each\ncomponent by adding them, while the with product takes their maximum.\n  In this work, we show that these products can be generalized to arbitrary\n$L^p$ distances, metrics that are often used in privacy and optimization. The\noriginal Fuzz products, tensor and with, correspond to the special cases $L^1$\nand $L^\\infty$. To ease the handling of such products, we extend the Fuzz type\nsystem with bunches -- as in the logic of bunched implications -- where the\ndistances of different groups of variables can be combined using different\n$L^p$ distances. We show that our extension can be used to reason about\nquantitative properties of probabilistic programs.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 3 Feb 2022 23:07:50 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 1 Feb 2023 19:32:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-03"}
